{"parentUuid":"174d8e56-e454-4b7e-ab64-c8e9af3e9138","isSidechain":false,"promptId":"d2c317cc-3f7b-4454-aeb3-a4d1136b5eae","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01BgxgQ6zJA8wx2HerkurHkN","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Embedding\n2\t\n3\t`git-sync` can now be used as a library as well as a CLI.\n4\t\n5\tFor most embedders, there are two important rules:\n6\t\n7\t- use `pkg/gitsync`\n8\t- avoid depending on `pkg/gitsync/unstable` unless you are acting like first-party tooling\n9\t\n10\t## Stable vs Unstable\n11\t\n12\tUse `pkg/gitsync` when you want a durable worker-facing API:\n13\t\n14\t- `Probe`\n15\t- `Plan`\n16\t- `Sync`\n17\t- typed requests and results\n18\t- injected auth and HTTP client support\n19\t\n20\tUse `pkg/gitsync/unstable` only when you need controls that are intentionally not yet stable:\n21\t\n22\t- `Bootstrap`\n23\t- `Fetch`\n24\t- batching knobs\n25\t- heap measurement\n26\t- verbose execution controls\n27\t- other engine-adjacent tuning\n28\t\n29\tThe CLI and benchmark command use `pkg/gitsync/unstable` because they still need those controls. External workers should generally not.\n30\t\n31\t## Worker Shape\n32\t\n33\tA queue worker usually wants:\n34\t\n35\t1. deserialize a job into source, target, scope, and policy\n36\t2. build a `gitsync.Client`\n37\t3. inject auth and an `http.Client`\n38\t4. call `Plan` or `Sync`\n39\t5. persist structured result data\n40\t6. decide success, retry, or escalation\n41\t\n42\tMinimal example:\n43\t\n44\t```go\n45\tpackage worker\n46\t\n47\timport (\n48\t\t\"context\"\n49\t\t\"net/http\"\n50\t\n51\t\t\"github.com/soph/git-sync/pkg/gitsync\"\n52\t)\n53\t\n54\tfunc runSync(ctx context.Context) error {\n55\t\tclient := gitsync.New(gitsync.Options{\n56\t\t\tHTTPClient: &http.Client{},\n57\t\t\tAuth: gitsync.StaticAuthProvider{\n58\t\t\t\tSource: gitsync.EndpointAuth{Token: \"source-token\"},\n59\t\t\t\tTarget: gitsync.EndpointAuth{Token: \"target-token\"},\n60\t\t\t},\n61\t\t})\n62\t\n63\t\tresult, err := client.Sync(ctx, gitsync.SyncRequest{\n64\t\t\tSource: gitsync.Endpoint{URL: \"https://github.example/source/repo.git\"},\n65\t\t\tTarget: gitsync.Endpoint{URL: \"https://git.example/target/repo.git\"},\n66\t\t\tScope: gitsync.RefScope{\n67\t\t\t\tBranches: []string{\"main\"},\n68\t\t\t},\n69\t\t\tPolicy: gitsync.SyncPolicy{\n70\t\t\t\tIncludeTags: true,\n71\t\t\t\tProtocol:    gitsync.ProtocolAuto,\n72\t\t\t},\n73\t\t})\n74\t\tif err != nil {\n75\t\t\treturn err\n76\t\t}\n77\t\n78\t\t_ = result\n79\t\treturn nil\n80\t}\n81\t```\n82\t\n83\t## Auth Injection\n84\t\n85\t`pkg/gitsync` uses one auth ownership model:\n86\t\n87\t- requests carry endpoint identity\n88\t- `AuthProvider` resolves source and target auth\n89\t\n90\tThat avoids baking CLI-style precedence rules into request types.\n91\t\n92\tGood uses of `AuthProvider`:\n93\t\n94\t- resolve OAuth tokens from your worker secret store\n95\t- attach different credentials for source and target\n96\t- centralize token refresh or lookup logic\n97\t\n98\tThe simplest option is `gitsync.StaticAuthProvider`, but a real worker will usually implement `AuthProvider` itself.\n99\t\n100\t## HTTP Injection\n101\t\n102\tPass an `*http.Client` through `gitsync.Options` when you need:\n103\t\n104\t- explicit timeouts\n105\t- custom TLS or proxy config\n106\t- OTEL or tracing round-trippers\n107\t- test transports\n108\t- custom connection pooling behavior\n109\t\n110\t`git-sync` clones and wraps the provided client internally so it can still collect transfer stats without mutating the caller's client directly.\n111\t\n112\t## Result Handling\n113\t\n114\tThe stable `SyncResult` is organized for worker consumption:\n115\t\n116\t- `Refs`\n117\t  per-ref outcomes and reasons\n118\t- `Counts`\n119\t  aggregate applied/skipped/blocked/deleted totals\n120\t- `Execution`\n121\t  protocol, relay summary, execution mode, and batch summary\n122\t- `Stats`\n123\t  transfer counters when requested\n124\t- `Measurement`\n125\t  only where exposed by the stable surface\n126\t\n127\tThat gives a worker enough structure to:\n128\t\n129\t- persist job history\n130\t- emit metrics\n131\t- log ref-level outcomes\n132\t- make retry/escalation decisions\n133\t\n134\t## Retry Guidance\n135\t\n136\tTreat these differently:\n137\t\n138\t- request construction and auth errors\n139\t  Usually configuration or secret-resolution issues. Retry only if your system expects credentials to become valid asynchronously.\n140\t- transport or remote errors returned from `Sync`\n141\t  Usually retryable depending on your queue policy and remote failure mode.\n142\t- successful `SyncResult` with blocked refs\n143\t  This is usually not a transport retry. It is a policy or repo-state outcome and should often be surfaced to operators.\n144\t\n145\tFor many workers, a useful pattern is:\n146\t\n147\t- retry on returned `error`\n148\t- do not blindly retry on `Counts.Blocked > 0`\n149\t- log `Execution.Mode` and `Execution.Reason` for operator visibility\n150\t\n151\t## What Not To Depend On\n152\t\n153\tIf you want stability, do not build external worker logic around:\n154\t\n155\t- batching thresholds\n156\t- max-pack controls\n157\t- materialized-object limits\n158\t- temp refs\n159\t- exact relay strategy names beyond coarse execution summary\n160\t\n161\tThose are implementation details or advanced controls that currently belong in `pkg/gitsync/unstable`, not the stable embedding contract.\n162\t"}]},"uuid":"c0c3ec40-50bc-4664-b8b9-68ad01dfc125","timestamp":"2026-04-13T15:27:16.593Z","toolUseResult":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/git-sync/docs/embedding.md","content":"# Embedding\n\n`git-sync` can now be used as a library as well as a CLI.\n\nFor most embedders, there are two important rules:\n\n- use `pkg/gitsync`\n- avoid depending on `pkg/gitsync/unstable` unless you are acting like first-party tooling\n\n## Stable vs Unstable\n\nUse `pkg/gitsync` when you want a durable worker-facing API:\n\n- `Probe`\n- `Plan`\n- `Sync`\n- typed requests and results\n- injected auth and HTTP client support\n\nUse `pkg/gitsync/unstable` only when you need controls that are intentionally not yet stable:\n\n- `Bootstrap`\n- `Fetch`\n- batching knobs\n- heap measurement\n- verbose execution controls\n- other engine-adjacent tuning\n\nThe CLI and benchmark command use `pkg/gitsync/unstable` because they still need those controls. External workers should generally not.\n\n## Worker Shape\n\nA queue worker usually wants:\n\n1. deserialize a job into source, target, scope, and policy\n2. build a `gitsync.Client`\n3. inject auth and an `http.Client`\n4. call `Plan` or `Sync`\n5. persist structured result data\n6. decide success, retry, or escalation\n\nMinimal example:\n\n```go\npackage worker\n\nimport (\n\t\"context\"\n\t\"net/http\"\n\n\t\"github.com/soph/git-sync/pkg/gitsync\"\n)\n\nfunc runSync(ctx context.Context) error {\n\tclient := gitsync.New(gitsync.Options{\n\t\tHTTPClient: &http.Client{},\n\t\tAuth: gitsync.StaticAuthProvider{\n\t\t\tSource: gitsync.EndpointAuth{Token: \"source-token\"},\n\t\t\tTarget: gitsync.EndpointAuth{Token: \"target-token\"},\n\t\t},\n\t})\n\n\tresult, err := client.Sync(ctx, gitsync.SyncRequest{\n\t\tSource: gitsync.Endpoint{URL: \"https://github.example/source/repo.git\"},\n\t\tTarget: gitsync.Endpoint{URL: \"https://git.example/target/repo.git\"},\n\t\tScope: gitsync.RefScope{\n\t\t\tBranches: []string{\"main\"},\n\t\t},\n\t\tPolicy: gitsync.SyncPolicy{\n\t\t\tIncludeTags: true,\n\t\t\tProtocol:    gitsync.ProtocolAuto,\n\t\t},\n\t})\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\treturn err\n\t}\n\n\t_ = result\n\treturn nil\n}\n```\n\n## Auth Injection\n\n`pkg/gitsync` uses one auth ownership model:\n\n- requests carry endpoint identity\n- `AuthProvider` resolves source and target auth\n\nThat avoids baking CLI-style precedence rules into request types.\n\nGood uses of `AuthProvider`:\n\n- resolve OAuth tokens from your worker secret store\n- attach different credentials for source and target\n- centralize token refresh or lookup logic\n\nThe simplest option is `gitsync.StaticAuthProvider`, but a real worker will usually implement `AuthProvider` itself.\n\n## HTTP Injection\n\nPass an `*http.Client` through `gitsync.Options` when you need:\n\n- explicit timeouts\n- custom TLS or proxy config\n- OTEL or tracing round-trippers\n- test transports\n- custom connection pooling behavior\n\n`git-sync` clones and wraps the provided client internally so it can still collect transfer stats without mutating the caller's client directly.\n\n## Result Handling\n\nThe stable `SyncResult` is organized for worker consumption:\n\n- `Refs`\n  per-ref outcomes and reasons\n- `Counts`\n  aggregate applied/skipped/blocked/deleted totals\n- `Execution`\n  protocol, relay summary, execution mode, and batch summary\n- `Stats`\n  transfer counters when requested\n- `Measurement`\n  only where exposed by the stable surface\n\nThat gives a worker enough structure to:\n\n- persist job history\n- emit metrics\n- log ref-level outcomes\n- make retry/escalation decisions\n\n## Retry Guidance\n\nTreat these differently:\n\n- request construction and auth errors\n  Usually configuration or secret-resolution issues. Retry only if your system expects credentials to become valid asynchronously.\n- transport or remote errors returned from `Sync`\n  Usually retryable depending on your queue policy and remote failure mode.\n- successful `SyncResult` with blocked refs\n  This is usually not a transport retry. It is a policy or repo-state outcome and should often be surfaced to operators.\n\nFor many workers, a useful pattern is:\n\n- retry on returned `error`\n- do not blindly retry on `Counts.Blocked > 0`\n- log `Execution.Mode` and `Execution.Reason` for operator visibility\n\n## What Not To Depend On\n\nIf you want stability, do not build external worker logic around:\n\n- batching thresholds\n- max-pack controls\n- materialized-object limits\n- temp refs\n- exact relay strategy names beyond coarse execution summary\n\nThose are implementation details or advanced controls that currently belong in `pkg/gitsync/unstable`, not the stable embedding contract.\n","numLines":162,"startLine":1,"totalLines":162}},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"174d8e56-e454-4b7e-ab64-c8e9af3e9138","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/git-sync","sessionId":"7b2777b1-8075-41f4-a62a-cbfc1b76c01b","version":"2.1.91","gitBranch":"soph/replicate","slug":"clever-popping-whisper"}
